<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910219-0117</DOCNO><DOCID>910219-0117.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   GE Capital Acquires   Virgin Vision of U.K.   In Chapter 11 Accord</HL><DATE>02/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11</SO><CO>   GE MCEGE</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- General Electric Capital Corp., a unit ofGeneral Electric Co., acquired Virgin Vision Ltd., a largeU.K. video distributor, as part of a settlement agreementwith Management Co. Entertainment Group Inc.   The agreement, which was approved by a federal bankruptcycourt judge here, gives GE Capital possession of the videodistributor in lieu of repayment of $82 million in secureddebt owed by MCEG. General Electric has another $10 millionin unsecured claims against MCEG, an independent moviecompany that grew rapidly and then collapsed.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;It is our intention to restore the value of Virgin Visionand position it for resale,&quot; said a spokeswoman for GECapital.   MCEG and many of its units have filed for protection fromcreditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws. Thecompany still owes payments to scores of Hollywood directors,producers and production-related companies. An MCEG spokesmansaid the company is planning to complete work on six moviesthat had been halted. The movies include &quot;Boris and Natasha,&quot;starring Sally Kellerman.   MCEG acquired Virgin Vision for $83 million in July of1989. The heavy debt load from the purchase contributed toMCEG's financial collapse. Analysts considered the dealoverpriced, and there were significant unresolved legalquestions about distribution rights.   Kidder, Peabody Group Inc., a New York-based investmentbanking unit of General Electric, had provided MCEG with abridge loan of $67 million for the acquisition. The loan waslater transferred to GE Capital as part of a largerportfolio, and GE Capital made a subsequent loan of $5million to Virgin Vision.   GE Capital, Stamford, Conn., is a financial services unitof GE, a diversified manufacturing, technology and servicescompany based in Fairfield, Conn.</TEXT></DOC>